post_text:
Lobos, two new updates have been added to bringbackthepack.unm.edu.
1. All students must complete the daily screening survey every day to continue protecting the pack.
2. There is now a targeted interventional COVID-19 testing site for students. Currently, this is only available for symptomatic students or students potentially exposed on campus. Please go to https://bit.ly/31gvaKf for more information.
To contact SHAC: http://shac.unm.edu/
Keep up the work of protecting each and every Lobo!

post_text: Forty-six years ago, student-athletes at The University of New Mexico boycotted to make a statement about racial inequality at UNM. Decades later, the contributions of those student-athletes have made a positive impact on UNM athletics. UNM football player Cedric Patterson III is joined by Dr. Harold Bailey (BS 1968, MA 1971, Ph.D. 1975), president of the Albuquerque NAACP and Ron Wallace (BS, MPA), Publisher of The Perspective, to discuss the significance of the 1974 UNM student-athlete boycott. New Mexico Lobos Watch more here:
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Racism: An Educational Series | 1974 Boycott

post_text:
"The entire UNM community mourns the passing of Rudolfo Anaya, one of the great voices not only of Chicano literature, but of humanity. He wrote of New Mexico, and what it meant to be a New Mexican--and did so in the same manner in which he lived his life: with passion, excitement, and conviction. During his long tenure as a teacher of writing at The University of New Mexico, he inspired countless students to find and raise their voices, to take pleasure in reading as well as great joy in writing and self-expression. His enthusiasm for his craft, as well as his unbreakable optimism, were infectious. We miss him‚Äîand our thoughts are with his family and friends.

"'I will live as long as you remember me,' Anaya once wrote. 'I live in your memory.' Rudolfo Anaya lives on in our memories, and in our hearts."

‚Äî UNM President Garnett S. Stokes

Read more about Rudolfo's writings and life here:

ANAYA.UNM.EDU

post_text: Today was supposed to be a day of closure for our class of 2020 Lobos at our favorite place in the world, the PIT. Instead, you may have watched a parade of your loved ones cheer you on in your driveway. It may have been spent on a zoom with your closest professors. And for a few of you, it may have been spent seemingly alone. But you will never be alone. You have always been a Lobo and you will always have the Pack. We hope to see you for your virtual celebration on May 30th and we can't wait to see you take those steps worth waiting for at an in-person commencement. #EveryStepLobos #UNMGrad

Instead, you may have watched a parade of your loved ones cheer you on in your driveway. It may have been spent on a zoom with your closest professors. And for a few of you, it may have been spent seemingly alone. But you will never be alone. You have always been a Lobo and you will always have the Pack. We hope to see you for your virtual celebration on May 30th and we can't wait to see you take those steps worth waiting for at an in-person commencement. #EveryStepLobos #UNMGrad

The most recent update on UNM's Period of Limited Operations: https://bit.ly/3bbnHyl

Key Points ‚¨áÔ∏è

- UNM is still open
- Many in-person classes will transition to online instruction.
- Some in-person classes that can not transition will have to be replaced with other forms or eliminated.
- We are committed to ensuring that every student approaching graduation will graduate.
- Areas on campus are now restricted to access to critical staff. These areas: the Health Sciences Center, Johnson Gym, the Student Union Building, Zimmerman and HSC Libraries, and others listed in the link at the top of this thread.
- The Dane Smith Hall facility will be available for students needing computer access.
- Food options will be limited to La Posada and the SRC Market for takeout only.
